ce:section.ce:para:
In order to break through the limitation of “trade-off”, based on the physicochemical structure of GO, we proposed a confined intercalation strategy utilizing pre-designed sulfonated graphene quantum dots (SGQD) to increase the ion exchange group contents of GO laminates without expanding the channel width and destructing the 2D regularity for GO laminates, thus achieving simultaneous improvements of ion permeability and selectivity (Fig. 1
                     ). SGQD is composed of sp2 carbon and thus the π-π interactions between SGQD and the graphene regions of GO are supportive of the spontaneous GO/SGQD composite assembly. More importantly, SGQD possesses an ultra-small size (9–14 nm) and ultra-thin thickness (∼0.4 nm), making it well-accommodated between the GO laminates. Correspondingly, the SGQD intercalation will not enlarge the GO 2D channels. On the other hand, SGQD has a high density of sulfonic acid groups surrounding the edge, which can increase the ion exchange sites and promote efficient ion migration. Meanwhile, the di-valent anions are subjected to stronger electrostatic repulsion by the negatively charged sulfonic acid groups compared to OH−, which can improve the ion selectivity of GO membranes. For treating simulated industrial wastewater NaOH/Na2WO4, the GO/SGQD membranes show ideal performances with OH− dialysis coefficients (UOH
                     −) of 3.5 × 10−3-8.2 × 10−3 m h−1 and separation factors (S) of 56–116. We demonstrate that the rational intercalation manipulation strategy for GO membranes has significant potential for the preparation of high performance 2D alkali recovery membranes with underlying industrial application prospects.
